            <div n="1">
                <head>SUBTERRANEAN NOISES.</head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The most striking instance of uninterrupted subterranean<lb break="yes"/>noise
                    unaccompanied by any trace of earthquake, is the<lb break="yes"
                    />ph&#x00E6;nomenon which is known in the Mexican territory by<lb break="yes"
                    />the name of &#x201C;the subterranean roaring and thundering<lb break="yes"
                    />(bramidos y truenos subterraneos) of Guanaxuato.&#x201D; This<lb break="yes"
                    />rich and celebrated mountain-city is situated at a distance<lb break="yes"
                    />from any active volcano. The noise began on the 9th<lb break="yes"/>January,
                    1784, at midnight, and lasted above a month. I<lb break="yes"/>have been enabled
                    to give a circumstantial description of<lb break="yes"/>the ph&#x00E6;nomenon
                    from the report of many witnesses, and<lb break="yes"/>from the documents of the
                    municipality which I was per-<lb break="no"/>mitted to make use of. From the
                    13th to the 16th of<lb break="yes"/>January, it was as if there were heavy
                    storm-clouds under<lb break="yes"/>the feet of the inhabitants, in which slow
                    rolling thunder<lb break="yes"/>alternated with short thunder-claps. The noise
                        ceased<lb break="yes"/>gradually, as it had commenced; it was confined to a
                        small<lb break="yes"/>space, for it was not heard in a basaltic district at
                    the dis-<lb break="no"/>tance of only a few miles. Almost all the inhabitants
                        were<lb break="yes"/>terrified and quitted the city, in which large masses
                        of<lb break="yes"/>silver were stored; but the most courageous, when they<lb
                        break="yes"/>had become somewhat accustomed to the subterranean<lb
                        break="yes"/>thunder, returned and fought with the bands of robbers<lb
                        break="yes"/>who had taken possession of the treasure. Neither at the<lb
                        break="yes"/>surface, nor in mines 1,598 English feet in depth, could the<lb
                        break="yes"/>slightest trembling of the ground be perceived. In no<lb
                        break="yes"/>part of the whole mountainous country of Mexico had<lb
                        break="yes"/>anything similar ever been known before; nor has this<lb
                        break="yes"/>awful ph&#x00E6;nomenon been since repeated. Thus, as chasms<lb
                        break="yes"/>in the interior of the earth close or open, the propagation<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the waves of sound is either arrested in its progress or<lb
                        break="yes"/>continued until it reaches the ear.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i"
                        >Humboldt&#x2019;s Cosmos.</hi>
                </p>
